text: The release of the 2004 Oregon Nursery and Greenhouse Survey results represents
label: BODY

text: the fifteenth year of documenting through statistics the progress of Oregon’s # 1
label: BODY

text: agricultural industry.  Nursery and greenhouse sales climbed to $ 844 million in 2004,
label: BODY

text: up 8 percent from the previous year, demonstrating that the industry continues to do an
label: BODY

text: outstanding job of growing and marketing high quality nursery stock and materials.
label: BODY

text: This growth continues despite the challenges of truck shortages, rising fuel,
label: BODY

text: transportation, and labor costs, sometimes burdensome regulations, and competition
label: BODY

text: for land.  The industry is a key generator of revenue for the State, with in excess of 75
label: BODY

text: percent of sales coming from outside Oregon.
label: BODY

text: Oregon’s top five producing counties Clackamas, Washington, Marion, Yamhill, and
label: BODY

text: Multnomah are in or near the Portland metropolitan area.  The nurseries and
label: BODY

text: greenhouses in these five counties represent 86 percent of the total value of production,
label: BODY

text: providing local employment and beautifying the urbanized landscape.

text: 2004 Oregon nursery product sales set another record.
label: HH2

text: Oregon’s horticulture industries continued to grow in 2004 with another record high sales value of $844 million for nursery and
label: BODY

text: greenhouse products.  This was the fifteenth year of this survey and the fourteenth year of record sales.  Sales in 2004 climbed 8
label: BODY

text: percent above 2003 and were over 2  times the sales of 1995.  The horticulture industry continued to solidify its place above all other
label: BODY

text: Oregon agricultural commodities, claiming nearly 21 percent of the total value of agricultural production.  Cattle, with a value of $503
label: BODY

text: million, ranked second, while all hay and all milk claimed third and fourth places with sales of $382 million and $363 million,
label: BODY

text: Seventy-two percent of the total $65 million sales increase this year was in Container sales, which increased 16 percent over last
label: BODY

text: year, while Bare Root products gained 6 percent.  Each category of plant material sales was higher in 2004 than in 2003, except for
label: BODY

text: the other product category which remained the same as the previous year.
label: BODY

text: Gross sales, when broken down by sales size groups, showed increases in all but one group. The largest size group, 2+ million,
label: BODY

text: increased 12 percent or $67.3 million over 2003. This increased value  is more than the total increase  because the $500,000 to $2
label: BODY

text: million sales size group was down 3 percent to 5.1 million from last year. This size group was down in sales value because many of
label: BODY

text: these firms increased sales and moved into the 2+ million size group.

text: Oregon’s top four counties of production, Clackamas, Washington, Marion, and Yamhill had with sales of $193.5 million, $191.2  million,
label: BODY

text: $178.9 million and $115.9 million, respectively. In  total, these four counties accounted  for 81 percent of all the sales. When Multnomah
label: BODY

text: county's  sales of $49.0 million is included, the total value of production in the top five counties account for 86 percent of total
label: BODY

text: production.  Clackamas county is still the major production area, but Marion county -- which has been the second largest county of
label: BODY

text: production -- was replaced by Washington county this year. Washington county sales were only 2.3 million below Clackamas county
label: BODY

text: and increased $27.5 million above last year. Given the number of growers and acres in production in Clackamas, Washington, and
label: BODY

text: Marion, counties, any of these three could be the number one producer next year.

text: The 2004 Oregon Nursery and Greenhouse Survey was designed to collect data on all commercial nurseries, greenhouses, and
label: BODY

text: producers of other plant material, such as roses, holly, bulbs, sod, cut flowers, dried flowers, etc. in the State. A stratified random
label: BODY

text: sample of 752 names was selected from the State of Oregon’s list of licensed nurseries and greenhouses for 2004. They were
label: BODY

text: classified into six broad size groups based on sales volume. The Oregon Agricultural Statistics Service's floriculture survey was used to
label: BODY

text: supplement the list for those firms  who are not required to have a State license.
label: BODY

text: Questionnaires were mailed to the sampled names on June 13, 2005, followed by a second request on July 7. All non-respondents
label: BODY

text: were phoned or visited from July 27 to August 18. Cooperation was excellent with 92 percent of the sampled names partaicipating in
label: BODY

text: the survey.  Data for minor counties and items were combined with other totals to avoid disclosure of individual operations.
label: BODY

text: The sample design was developed by the National Agricultural Statistics Service. Kent Hoddick of the Oregon Staff has been the
label: BODY

text: survey coordinator of the Oregon Nursery and Greenhouse program since its inception in 1991.

text: Percentage wise, the following destinations showed the strongest gains from the last destination survey in 1999:  Other Western States - up 46 percent ($19.2 million); Upper
label: BODY

text: Midwest - up 67 percent ($52.9 million); Gulf States - up 39 percent ($6.9 million); Northeast States - up 48 percent ($39.4 million); and Eastern Canada - up 146 percent ($11.1
label: BODY

text: million).  All other destinations also increased but at lesser percent changes.  Of course, Oregon remained the largest destination, increasing by $30.2 million dollars in sales
label: BODY

text: delivered over 1999.  Destination sales as a percent of total Oregon sales produced showed increased sales in Other Western States, Upper Midwest, Gulf States, Northeast
label: BODY

text: States, and Eastern Canada,  while all other regions declined in sales value share. Virtually all regions showed strong gains in container sales delivered over 1999.  Most regions
label: BODY

text: showed good gains in Balled & Burlapped deliveries except Upper Midwest - no change, Atlantic States - declined, Northeast States - declined, and Eastern Canada - declined.
label: BODY

text: Bare root deliveries made modest gains in all regions except Oregon showed a slight decline.  The Upper Midwest increased about 75 percent in deliveries for bare root material.
label: BODY

text: Greenhouse and Other plant materials made good gains overall.
